> unfortunately, our government won’t be honest with them. cronyism isn’t capitalism

&nbsp;

Isn’t cronyism just capitalism without sufficient regulations and checks and balances? All business is attempting to gain more market share & profit, and one of the best ways to do that is to make sure whatever governing body you exist under supports your business. 

&nbsp;

To me this is just a natural conclusion of what unchecked capitalism does. Not exactly a feature, more like a bug that you have to create guard rails for, right? 

&nbsp;

> if voters understood that, we’d be a lot closer to be a freer society.

&nbsp;

Don’t voters already understand this? From my perspective anyone I’ve ever talked to understands that companies and people alike get lots of support from the government. Many just believe that the the rich get an undue amount of support, and we should swing to giving more support to the general population. 

&nbsp;

> concentrated power creates wealth disparity.

&nbsp;

Isn’t this why there is so much vitriol against billionaires and large companies nowadays? Many people understand that concentrated power exists amongst those classes and that the current iteration of capitalism is just entrenching their power.

&nbsp; 

They no longer believe that the current system can right itself so-to-speak and want to attempt a new one. 

&nbsp;

To me this is the same reason why Trump became so popular, he spoke about changing the system to better people’s lives. Now in my opinion, he’s done the exact opposite at mostly all turns. But his message resonated with people who intrinsically understood that the game was rigged against them by entrenched powers, right?

